@node hist "History"
5.0.0 First international version.
        The German version has been translated to an
      English version by executing a program which
      converts the source code of MicroBase.
        (* first package *)
5.0.1 Optimized the reorganization and pack processes.
        Better documentation.
        "cbsi" detects Amiga OS 3.9.
        MicroBase has been tested with Amiga OS 3.9.
        Amiga OS 3.9 ships with a new version of
      "rexxmathlib.library", thus the version shiped
      with MicroBase is not installed.
        "cxb.library" has been compiled using Creative
      E 2.1.
        MicroBase shuts down faster now. The old
      procedure called inefficient commands.
5.0.2 The personalization of MicroBase failed so that
      the program could not be used - fixed.
        Some localization problems have been fixed.
        Fields may be added or deleted.
        Some minor bugs have been fixed.
        (* second package *)
5.0.3 "mbbrowser" shows all fields correctly. Previous
      versions corrupted the contents of the first
      field.
        Records containing German umlauts are
      sorted correctly now.
        <SHIFT>+<cursor keys> works (jumps to the first or
      last character of the input field, respectively).
        MicroBase maintains a list of last recently used
      database files.
        (* third package *)
5.0.4 XML export revised. You should always convert German umlauts
      in order to avoid problems with WWW browsers.
        Fixed spell error in German version of MicroBase.
        dBASE conversion has been tested with Approach of "Lotus
      SmartSUITE 9.7 (Windows XP Home Edition).
        Fixed the personalization process.
        *** This is the first English version which can actually be
      used. The former versions had an incorrect localization which
      caused the personalization process to crash.
@endnode

@node intro "Introduction"
MicroBase is a relational database management system using random access
files.

In order to get a description of the input required by the application,
simply hit the "Help" key. This brings up a dialog box explaining
which kind of input is expected.

@{b}Database creation@{ub}

To create a database, perform the following steps:

(1) Write down the fields you want to use (name, type, length) and
    the total amount of fields.

(2) Create the database.

(3) Select a password if you want the database file to
    be encrypted.

@{b}Using databases@{ub}

The menu items of the "Record" menu allow you to:

o  add records
o  browse the database
o  sort the database
o  search and replace values through the whole database

@{b}References@{ub}

References are used to link other databases to yours.

This must be done within the creation of the database.

MicroBase uses reference caches to speed up the
resolution of external references. Due to this feature,
saving the record or viewing it for the first time
takes more time. The next access will be extremely
fast, however.

@{b}Unique features@{ub}

MicroBase uses a transaction system in order to recover
quickly after system crashes or power failure.

Databases may be used by multiple users at the same time.
Records and databases are locked if one user needs
write access. (Read access is never locked.)

ARexx scripts may be written in order to achieve
complex selections or reports.
@endnode

@node menus "Menus"
@{b}Project@{ub}

New    Chose a name for your new database file (".dat" will be
       added) and type in the number of fields you want to
       use per record. (Default: one field.)

       For each field, enter the following information:

       o  field name (may contain spaces, German umlauts, and symbols)
       o  field type
       o  field length
       o  default (default contents of the field)
       o  options (e. g. convert to lower case)

       To get a description of the data expected by MicroBase, simply
       hit the "Help" key.

       Enter a password (up to 60 characters) if you want your database
       file to be encrypted. Enter "$" in order to select a password
       file (up to 16 KB).

       Notes: (1) There are 191 ^ 60 = 10 ^ 137 possible passwords
                  of 60 characters (no control characters).

              (2) There are 256 ^ 16384 = 10 ^ 39457 possible password
                  files of 16 KB length (including control characters).
                  Calculation: 39457 = (log(256) * 16384) / log(10)

       When MicroBase asks you to confirm the creation of the database,
       hit <Enter>.

Open   Closes the current database file and opens another one. If
       the database to be opened is encrypted, enter the password.
       (Enter "$" in order to select a password file.)

Close  Closes the current database file. (This may take a while.)

Delete Deletes a database file and all other files that are used by
       the database file (defaults, options, etc.). The current
       database file cannot be deleted.

Last   Displays a list of last recently used database files and
       asks you to enter the number of the database file you want
       to be opened.

       Enter 0 (zero) to abort this operation. Otherwise, the
       current database file will be closed before opening the
       selected database file.

About  Displays an About dialog.

       Optionally some statistics of the MicroBase relational
       database management system may be displayed:

       o  database file
       o  number of records
       o  virtual memory usage
       o  percentage of records selected by the user
       o  the percentage of free resources (should be above 70 %)

Quit   Quits MicroBase.

@{b}Edit@{ub}

Input  Adds a new record to the database.

       Again, hit the "Help" key for more information.


         Key              Action
         ------------------------------------------------
         <Help>           displays a help message
         <left>           moves cursor left
         <right>          moves cursor right
         <Shift>+<left>   moves cursor to first character
         <Shift>+<right>  moves cursor to last character
         <Esc>            empties input field


       Optionally, input templates are generated by MicroBase:

       o  "  /  /    " for dates
       o  "  :  :  " for time values

       If your database uses references and "preserve reference
       integrity" has not been disabled, you cannot save a record until
       its content is consistent with the database your database refers
       to. This feature slows down data inputs, but ensures that the
       databases can be referenced.

       If your database uses references and "preserve reference
       integrity" has been disabled, rebuild the reference caches now.

Browse Browses through the records of your database.

       Again, hit the <Help> key for further information.

       The mouse bar at the bottom of the screen corresponds to the
       keys mentioned by the help message.

       The "s" key is used to (de)select a record, for instance.

Delete Deletes all records which are currently selected.

Sort   Sorts the whole database by using virtual memory.

       You may change the field type and the direction (ascending,
       descending).

Search Searches for records using "query by example".

       You may configure MicroBase to be case sensitive.

       Phonetic search is only of use for German users of MicroBase
       at the moment.

       This process shares its criteria with the "Update" command.

Update Performs a search and replace process. Disable the
       recalculation of formulae to accelerate the process. (This is
       the default if no calculation fields are defined.)

Open   Opens a file containing criteria used by "Update".

Save   Saves the criteria used by "Update" to a file.

Reset  Deletes the search and update criteria.

Selection        Enables or disables the selection.
Select All       Selects all records.
Selection Matrix Opens or saves a selection matrix file.

@{b}Database@{ub}

Import  Imports a sequential file into the current database or
        into a new database file.

        The field separator may be defined by the user. (We
        recommend TAB characters.) Enter the ASCII code
        of the field seperator (e. g. "9") or precede a
        character with a backtick (e. g. "`,").

        If the first record of the sequential file contains
        field names, it may be discarded by the "Input" process
        in case you wish so.

Export  Exports the current database to a sequential file (see
        above for details).

Extract Copies the records which are currently selected to a new
        MicroBase database file.

Lists   You may edit, open, save, and print a report (list).
        The default destination for printing is the printer
        ("PRT:"). Enter "w" to print to an output window
        or "$" to select a file.

Labels  Labels are lists which are restricted to 9 lines of
        input. They are used for addresses on envelopes
        (corresponding to German standards).

Statistics     Calculates the average or total sum of all
               records currently selected.

Reorganize     Tries to repair a database file. This may take
               some time.

               Optionally, the database file may be "packed". This means
               that all records of the database file are copied to a new
               database file which is then given the name of the old one.

               "Pack" a database if you want to eliminate the records
               you tried to delete (deleting a record does not affect
               the size of the database file).

Rebuild Caches Rebuilds the reference caches if the current database is
               linked to other database files.

               Perform this process after updating or sorting a database
               in order to speed up the access to the database files
               linked to yours.

@{b}Extras@{ub}

New CLI         Opens a new CLI / Shell window.

dBASE Databases Converts, edits, or displays a dBASE database file.

                dBASE is a database standard used for IBM personal
                computers. (Amiga SuperBase IV can deal with
                dBASE files, too.)

                See @{" Modules " link modules} for details.

Run Script      Runs a MicroBase ARexx script.

                ARexx' "RexxMaster" server process must be running.

                In order to be able to use windows and dialogs, try
                the "MicroRexx" package which is available via
                Aminet.

Create Chart    Creates a project file for "MicroChart".

                The "MicroChart" package -- which draws bar,
                line, and pie charts -- is also available via
                Aminet.

Export to HTML  Exports the database to an HTML document.

Database -> Archive Creates an archive of the database.

Archive -> Database Creates a database of an archive file.

@{b}Options@{ub}

Preferences      Opens the "Preferences" editor.

                 "Show input templates"  displays a template for
                                         date and time fields

                 "Ignore case"           searches case insensitive
                 "Phonetic search"       performs a phonetic
                                         search (German only)
                 "Partial replace"       only replaces the matching
                                         part of the field content
                                         (default: replace the whole
                                         content)

                 "Hide references"       does not display reference
                                         fields
                 "Highlight references"  displays reference fields in
                                         italics
                 "Preserve reference integrity" all data you enter is
                                         checked and must correspond to
                                         the database which is linked
                                         to yours
                 "Delete invalid references" all records violating the
                                         reference integrity are deleted
                                         automagically when the reference
                                         caches are rebuilt

                 "Virtual mode"          stores the selection matrix on
                                         disk rather than in memory and
                                         allows the usage of more than
                                         2,000,000,000 records
                 "Multi user mode"       after enabling this option,
                                         MicroBase may be used in a
                                         network (write access locks
                                         either a record or the whole
                                         database)
                 "Compatibility mode"    slows MicroBase down and
                                         should only be used if you
                                         have problems (corrupt
                                         database files, unable
                                         to sort a file)

Change Structure Allows you to change the structure (field names
                 and types) of your database.

                 Notes:

                 o  some field types cannot be converted
                 o  field lengths cannot be changed yet

Delete Field     After asking for your confirmation, the
                 field is deleted. Its content will be
                 lost.

                 This process uses a temporary file and
                 closes the database file after deleting
                 the field.

Append Field     A field may be added. It is inserted behind the
                 existing fields.

                 This process uses a temporary file and
                 closes the database file after deleting
                 the field.

Personalization  Opens the "Personalization" tool.

                 If you are a registered user of MicroBase, you must
                 personalize your copy of the program. Otherwise,
                 your key file will be ignored.

                 The personalization activates your key file,
                 thus removing the limit of 20 records and
                 enabling "virtual mode".
@{b}Help@{ub}

Contents   Displays the document you are actually reading.

Tutorial   @{i}(Still not available)@{ui}
@endnode

@node modules "Modules"
The "Modules" directory contains the following utilities:


  Utility    Description
  --------------------------------------------------
  asc2dat    converts a text file to a
             MicroBase database
  dat2dbf    converts a MicroBase database to
             a dBase database file (for data exchange
             with Windows applications)
  dat2frm    converts a MicroBase database to
             an "asc2frm" source file ("asc2frm"
             is a text formatting package which
             is distributed as a separate archive
             via Aminet)
  dat2html   converts a MicroBase database to
             a table within an HTML document
  dat2latex  converts a MicroBase database to
             a table within a LaTeX document
             (change the font size or orientation
             of the table in order to see all
             of its columns)
  dat2sql    converts a MicroBase database to
             an SQL script which creates the
             database (tested with "SQLDB")
  dat2xml    converts a MicroBase database to an
             XML file -- an XSL file may be created
             if you wish so
  dB_Editor  an editor for dBase files
  dbf2asc    converts a dBase database to a
             text file
  dbf2dat    converts a dBase database to a
             MicroBase database
  dbview     displays the contents of a
             dBase database
  html2asc   converts the table(s) of an
             HTML document to text file(s)
  sbf2dat    converts a SuperBase IV database
             file to a MicroBase database
             (only text fields are supported)
  xml2asc    converts an XML file to a
             text file (experimental)


@{b}Remarks@{ub}

o If you want to keep the structure of your database,
  you should use dBASE databases or XML files.

o As mentioned above, only SuperBase databases
  containing text fields are supported. In order
  to achieve this, the field types of the
  database to be converted have to be changed.

  After that, the database has to be reorganized
  in order to actually change the structure
  of the database.

  Note: The conversion of German umlauts may
        fail, because they are treated
        differently by SuperBase.

o HTML documents may contain several tables.
  Each table is converted to a separate text
  file.

o The utilities do not support encrypted databases.

o Some characters must not be used within XML and
  HTML documents (e. g. "&").

o You should always convert German umlauts to XML
  in order to avoid problems with WWW browsers.

o dBASE conversion has been tested with "Lotus
  SmartSUITE 9.7" (database management software
  Apprpoach).
@endnode

@node refs "References"
References are links between database files.

In order to refer to another database file, the following
setup is required:

o  one or two key fields of the current database which identify
   a record of the other database
o  the database to be linked to
o  the field of the database yours refers to
o  the length of the field you want to refer to

References use "reference caches" in order to find the
corresponding record of the second database as fast as
possible. Enable he "strict references" option or
rebuild the reference caches after altering the
contents of the databases.
@endnode

@node scr "Scripts"
Scripts are written using ARexx. They are processed for each record
of the current database file separately.

Hint: If you need global variables, use the clip list of ARexx.

You have read access to all of the following variables:


  Variable      Type     Remarks
  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  fieldnnn      String   These variables represent the contents of
                         the fields (nnn = number within range 1..234)

  mroname       String   This is the name of the output file which
                         *must* be generated by your script. The scripts
                         shipping with MicroBase write the new field contents
                         and "selected" to that file.

  recno         Number   The number of the current record.

  reccount      Number   The total amount of records.

  recmax        Number   The maximum amount of records.

  recsel        Number   The amount of records which are selected.

  dbname        String   The name of the current database file.

  idxname       String   The name of the file containing the selection
                         matrix.

  mrxname       String   The name of the current script file.

  fields        Number   The number of fields each record consists of.

  selected      Number   Is this record selected?
                         0: No, it is not selected
                         Other: Yes, it is selected.


You may change the value of the "fieldnnn" and "selected" variables.
@endnode

@node ops "Search and Update"
Search and update use tags for search and update criteria.

Notes:

o  "empty" criteria is always considered to be "true"
o  criteria containing tags is always case sensitive
o  criteria without tags is considered to be a text string

@{b}Examples: Search@{ub}

  Meier                    searches for 'MeIer', 'Meier-Lehmann' etc.
  §§$==Meier               searches for 'Meier' only
                           (empty criteria: true!)
  §§$==                    searches for an empty field (of use for
                             deletion of unused records)
  §§%<>200                 searches for numbers, but not for 200
  §§%<<10000               searches for numbers below 10,000
  §§%>>6100                searches for numbers above 6,100
  §§%<=0                   searches for numbers less than or equal to 0
  §§%>=0                   searches for numbers above or equal to 0

If you try to use a tag beginning with §§% with a string, the value of
that string is considered to be 0 (zero).

@{b}Examples: Update@{ub}

  §§%++Value               adds <Value> to the current value of the
                             field
  §§%--Value               subtracts <Value>
  §§%//Value               divides the current value of the field
                             by <Value>
  §§%**Value               multiplies with <Value>
  2000                     new field content: '2000'
  hello                    new field content: 'hello'

@{b}Partial Replace@{ub}

By default, always the entire content of a field is replaced.

If "partial replace" is enabled, only the part of the field which
corresponds to the search criteria is replaced.

Note: Tags should not be used in conjunction with "partial replace".
@endnode

@node calc "Calculations"
In calculation formulae, you may refer to the following data:

Data         Remarks
------------------------------------------------------------------
fieldnnn     The content of field nnn (nnn within range 1..234)
#Constant    A global constant defined in the "MicroBase.cvd" file

@{b}Sample "MicroBase.cvd@{ub}

/* MICROBASE.CVD */
NUMERIC DIGITS 14

#pi = 3.141592653589793
#e  = 2.718281828459045

This file defines the constants ¶ and e and activates the maximum
accuracy of ARexx.

@{b}Example@{ub}

Imagine that you are calculating prices.

o  Field #1 contains the net price.
o  Field #2 calculates the price.
o  "MicroBase.cvd" contains the folowing line:
   #VAT = 0.12

In order to calculate the price, assign the following formula
to field #2:

field1 * (1.0 + #VAT)
@endnode

@node types "Data Types"
The following data types are available:

Data Type   Contents
-------------------------------------------------------
Text        Any string of up to 2,048 characters
Number      Any number consisting of up to 19 digits
            (including decimal point)
Date        A date like DD/MM/YYYY
Time        A time: HH:MM:SS
External    A link to an external file (up to 2,048
            characters) in combination with a viewer
            which is associated with the field (defaults
            to "Multiview")
            MicroBase ships with some viewers for use
            with Amiga OS 2.x.
Logical     A Boolean value (t,f,y,n,?)
Reference   A reference to another database file
Calculation A calculation formula
@endnode

@node misc "Other Topics"
Database conversion:  Have a look at the @{" Modules " link modules} directory.

Utilities:            Have a look at the @{" Utils " link utils} directory.

                      In most cases, you should get a short description
                      of the utilities by calling them with "?" as the
                      only argument.

Database creation:    Read a book about relational / SQL database
                      design (Entity Relationship Model,
                      database normalization), for example:

                      "The essence of databases", written by Fred D.
                      Rolland, published by Prentice Hall Europe
                      in 1998.
@endnode

