@node inst "Installation"
@{b}Requirements@{ub}

MicroBase requires Amiga OS Release 2.0 or above,
2 MB of hard disk space and 1 MB of RAM.

If you want to use large databases, you should use
the "MEMORY" ToolType of MicroBase. Increase the value
starting with "MEMORY=180" until the "Project/About"
menu item shows that the amount of free resources is
above 70 %.


@{b}Amiga OS 3.5 / 3.9 Deactivation@{ub}

MicroBase does not support the Amiga OS 3.5 and 3.9
versions of the »SetPatch« utility.

To be able to deactivate »SetPatch« while the Amiga
is booting by holding down the "F9" key, change the
following line of your »S:Startup-Sequence« file

       C:SetPatch QUIET

to

       KeyPressed 88
       If Not Warn
         C:SetPatch QUIET
       EndIf

Note: This procedure disables some features of
      Amiga OS 3.5.


@{b}Installation@{ub}

MicroBase is installed via an Installer script.

Most of the files are installed within the installation
directory.

The following files are stored on your system disk:

  File                 Directory
  ----------------------------------
  MicroBase.ini        ENV:, ENVARC:
  cbsi                 C:
  cxbar                C:
  cxbupd               C:
  keypressed           C:
  cxb.library          LIBS:
  hbasic2.library      LIBS:
  rexxmathlib.library  LIBS:

Note: "rexxmathlib.library" is not installed if
      a more recent version is detected
      (Amiga OS 3.9).

Some (hidden) directories are created within the
program directory:

  Directory  Description
  ------------------------------------------------------------
  res        This directory contains message files.
  recovery   This directory is used by the transaction service
             and should not be changed manually.
  vm         This directory contains the temporary files
             used by the virtual memory service. You may
             delete its contents if you are sure that
             nobody tries to access the database at
             the moment.
@endnode

@node features "Features"
This chapter consists of the following sections:

- General
- Databases and field types
- Printing
- Data exchange
- Security
- Data manipulation
- Linking database files
- Multi user mode
- Scripts
- World Wide Web

@{b}General@{ub}

o random access files

o "virtual mode": selection matrices are swapped to disk,
  leading to less memory consumption and allowing the
  usage of very large databases

o external preferences utility

o external database browser with GUI

o up to 234 fields per record

o up to 2,048 characters per field

o up to 65,535 records per file

o up to 2,000,000,000 records per file in "virtual mode"

o user-definable constants may be used in calculations
  (current VAT percentage, for instance)

o sample databases are provided

o progress indicator

o maintains a list of last recently used database files


@{b}Databases and field types@{ub}

o field names may consist of up to 20 characters (including
  blanks)

o field types: Number, Time, Date, eXternal (links to other files
  like pictures), Logical, Calculation, Reference (links to
  other database files)

o default values (text, current date / time, incremental)

o serial numbers with start value and increment (max. one per
  record)

o input templates for date and time (optional)

o supports decimal, binary, hexadecimal, and octal numbers
  in +/- 10 ^ 309 range

o database structure may be changed at any time (field
  lengths cannot be changed yet)

o type-sensitive help for data entry (just hit the <Help>
  key)

o viewers for external fields are selectable (your word
  processor, for instance)

o calculations

o field options (ranges, input required, conversion to
  lower / upper case)

o ships with viewers for Amiga OS 2.x

o checks for data consistency (you can't enter
  29 Feb 1900 like with Microsoft Excel)

o simple mouse bar in "browse mode"

o you may supply a help message for each field


@{b}Printing@{ub}

o output of labels and lists to printer or file

o includes template for mail merge

o number formatting (converts "1234.567" to "DM 1.234,57",
  for instance)

o saves MicroChart project files

o ships with a list file generator


@{b}Data exchange@{ub}

o imports and exports ASCII files of SuperBase Professional 4,
  BECKERtext III, Documentum 2, ProWrite, TransWrite, Personal
  Write

o may be adapted to other ASCII file formats

o ASCII files may be imported into the current database
  or converted to a new MicroBase database

o selected records may be copied to a new MicroBase file

o exports, imports and converts dBase database files

o provides both a dBase viewer and editor

o imports SuperBase files (Text fields only)

o automatically converts foreign database files

o provides an HTML publisher

o converts HTML tables to ASCII files

o exports LaTeX / TeX documents

o exports to asc2frm files

o fields enclosed by quotes may contain field delimiters

o external query utilities

o exports SQL scripts

o import and export of XML files


@{b}Security@{ub}

o optional encryption of database files

o reorganization of corrupt databases

o if a database to be opened seems to be corrupt,
  MicroBase reorganizes (recovers its data) automatically.

o error recovery: uses a transaction service

o password files may be used (up to 16,000 bytes)

o provides a password file generator utility

o personalization is required

o database files may be archived (cxbar / cxbupd utility)


@{b}Data manipulation@{ub}

o different sort modes for text, numerical, date,
  and time fields

o flexible search and update routines (field contents may
  be divided by a constant value, for instance)

o filter

o statistics: total sum, average, min., max.

o sorts database files "in place" by using virtual
  memory

o phonetic search / sort algorithms (German only)

o partial replace (replacing only a part of the
  previous field content)

o simple deletion of records

o "packing" a database deletes unused records (like
  dBase)


@{b}Linking database files@{ub}

o References (links to other databases) require no
  disk space

o reference caches for a fast resolution of links

o reference integrity

o deletes records violating the reference integrity
  (optional)

o checks for reference integrity during data entry
  (optional, default)


@{b}Multi user mode@{ub}

o locks records / databases

o a database file may be used by many users at the same
  time


@{b}Scripts@{ub}

o ARexx scripts may be executed

o records may be selected via ARexx scripts

o scripts allow complex calculations and may alter all
  fields

o use "MicroRexx" if you need dialog boxes, gadgets, or menus


@{b}World Wide Web@{ub}

o HTML publisher

o imports HTML tables

o external query utility outputs HTML tables and may be used
  with CGI scripts

o supports XML and XSL
@endnode

@node utils "Utilities"
MicroBase ships with the following utilities:


  Utility     Description
  ---------------------------------------------------------------------
  makelist     creates lists from .DEF files (table or form)
  ConvertList  converts lists from MicroBase 1.x/2.x to 3.0+
  VIEW         ANSI text viewer
  /dfree       calculates the free disk space (in bytes)
  C:CBSI       system information and benchmarks (MIPS, FLOPS)
  makepwd      creates password files
  delcode      processes text files and deletes control characters,
               duplicate blank lines etc.
  C:cxbar      an archiver
  C:cxbupd     updates archives
  mbbackup     backups databases to archives
  mbrestore    restores databases from archives
  query        performs an external query (requires "asc2frm")
  simplequery  performs an external query (uses standard output)
  webquery     performs an external query (outputs an HTML file
               and may be used within CGI scripts)
  mkmba        creates a query file for use with *query
  *query!      shell scripts simplifying external queries by allowing
               you to specify a database file with search criteria,
               for instance "simplequery! customers.dat Name Mike~Smith".
               The field names must not contain blanks. If the
               search criteria needs blanks, they must be
               replaced by "~" characters.


Note: The utilities do not support encrypted databases.
@endnode

@node list "Lists and Labels"
Lists and labels may contain the following tags:

Tag   Result
-----------------------------------------------
§f    Font: bold
§u    Font: underline
§i    Font: italics
§n    Font: plain / normal
§h    Font: superscript
§t    Font: subscript
§m    Font: superscript / subscript = off
§#    record number
§s    form feed
&nnn  displays the content of a field (full length)
%nnn  displays the content of a field (actual length)
#nnn  displays the name of a field

Note: nnn is a number within range 001..234.
@endnode


